data.contentText:
Calculate Full Thomson Score

Provide supportive care with the following

metadata.text1:
NB Fisting and cycling movements- fisting can be normal. To be abnormal, the fist must be so tight it's difficult to open.
See below for images of strong distal flexion and decerebrate posturing

Mild HIE: Thompson score 1- 10
Moderate HIE: Thompson score 11-14
Severe HIE: Thompson score >15
metadata.text2:
Kangaroo mother care/radiant warmer unless patient is hyperthermic

Put on appropriate respiratory support

Avoid hyperoxia or hypocarbia as both are associated with poor outcome.
Picture below is decerebrate posturing
metadata.text3:
For mild/moderate
- Give NG feeds: most will have a poor suck reflex 
- Mother can still offer breast to develop the suck reflex
- Check blood glucose & give dextrose bolus if BS <45mg/dL or < 2.5mmol/L
- Monitor blood glucose 4 hourly

For severe HIE, where feeds are not tolerated, consider IV fluids at restricted rate: 40-50ml/kg/day until Urine Output = 1ml/kg/hour 
Use 10% dextrose for first 24 hours, then additives can be used once renal function stabilised.

If evidence of seizure activity (CAN BE SUBTLE):
- give PHENOBARBITONE loading dose and go to the CONVULSIONS page 
- reassess suck, tone, coma, seizures every 8 hours for 72 hrs in hospital 

Treat for sepsis with antibiotics

If Anuric/oliguric: 
-consider catheterisation if bladder palpable
-Withold second/subsequent aminoglycoside doses.
metadata.title3: 3. Feeding and renal support, anticonvulsants and antibiotics
